			<div class="content" id="post-content-1210316">
									

<p>Pretty much agreed there, but</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I'd rather these be protists than worms.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I agree that these would be better as something other than worms, but I heavily dislike the term &quot;protists&quot; because the extent of what unifies them as a group is that they don't belong to any other kingdoms, and they're usually pretty simple. In other words, &quot;protist&quot; is just an informal way of saying &quot;none of the above&quot;. They're not consistently considered a valid way of grouping organisms. <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protist">A link.</a></p>
<p>It is mildly intriguing how a group of worms could replicate the organ systems, but that's not enough to carry the article and I sincerely doubt that it was intended to. In my opinion, these could be amoebas (still &quot;protists&quot;, but a legitimate genus that just doesn't fit into a pre-existing kingdom). Given the large amounts of, er, <em>biomass</em> that passes through any given plumbing system, 840 could probably <em>construct</em> a full digestive system, operated manually by the colony.</p>
<p>Alternatively, they could go man-o-war style and say &quot;fuck you, I am an organ&quot; and be organs, looking like the pipes just one day grew a digestive system for the hell of it, which is what I think you're going for here.</p>
<p>And it would just make my day if a plumber stuck his arm down the drain to see what was up and the drain ate his arm.</p>

