			<div class="content" id="post-content-1212449">
									

<p>I like it. +1. A few minor issues:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>large colonies consisting of many thousands or millions of individuals</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Scale problem: that's nowhere <em>near</em> enough of them. Cells are tiny. Try billions. (There are several trillion cells in the human body, for reference.)</p>
<blockquote>
<p>These fused colonies are capable of replicating many of the functions of organic tissues, particularly that of vital organs.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>You might want to specify that you mean <em>animal</em> tissues and organs.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Using the exterior of the pipe as an exoskeleton SCP-840 will, over time, convert <strong>these</strong> in to an extended digestive system</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The pronoun in bold is dangling: what does it refer to? The pipes?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>In larger drainage spaces, such as places where piping has burst (either incidentally or as a result of a build-up of SCP-840)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>And now I'm envisioning the main wet-wall of some big institutional building, the pipes one by one cracking open, a dense matrix of dripping tissue quietly filling the space behind the walls&#8230; AUGH. Nice one. :D My point is that this is sufficient to conjure that image: you could leave out some of the more explicit detail later in the article, and still cause plenty of <a href="http://www.urbandictionary.com/define.php?term=shit%20bricks">ceramics excretion</a>.</p>

							</div>

